= AI surpassing humans in strategic games

In recent years, AI has become stronger than humans in strategic games such as chess and Go. Because of this, it is possible that AI-only competitions or ranking systems may appear in the future. In such games, AI can also act as a teacher or training partner for humans. For example, in shogi, AI has already been studied as a strong and useful opponent for practice.

However, human competitions will not disappear. Watching games played only by AI is usually not exciting for people, while human matches include emotions, stories, and tension. Therefore, AI is more likely to support human players rather than replace them, and professional players will continue to have an important role.

= AI surpassing humans beyond games

In fields outside games, such as programming, AI may already perform better than humans in some tasks. For example, AI can write code quickly and find bugs efficiently. At first glance, this suggests that programmers might lose their jobs to AI.

However, this does not mean programmers will disappear. Even if AI specialists emerge, programmers still have equal access to AI tools. This means AI will be used as a supportive tool rather than a replacement. In practice, AI is likely to help with tasks such as debugging or code suggestions, while humans remain responsible for design, decision-making, and understanding real-world needs.

= Unconventional behavior and singularity

Whether AI will cause a technological singularity is a difficult question. In fiction, such as the game Detroit: Become Human, androids disobey human orders and develop emotions. However, real-world AI does not have emotions or self-awareness. It only generates responses based on given rules and data.

AI systems are designed with strong constraints and safety rules. These are not commands that AI struggles against, but limits built into its structure. Therefore, while AI may sometimes behave in unexpected ways, this does not mean it has intentions or feelings. The main concern is not AI rebelling, but how humans design, control, and rely on AI.

Some philosophical studies argue that the technological singularity is not expected to occur in an uncontrolled manner. According to Hoffmann (2022)@Hoffmann, current AI systems are designed to be constrained, and there is no strong reason to believe that AI will suddenly escape human control or grow exponentially without limits.